We must “recover” from this list of transactions only those amounts that “would go to” our accounts receivable (and also interest receivable that we treat as AR). In our system, none of the Initial entries are “accounts receivable” (only cash, bank or fixed‐assets appear); therefore the AR “balance at the beginning” is zero.

Then, when we inspect the transactions that post to “accounts receivable” we note that only some of the “Sale” transactions – those whose “receive_method” column is set to “Account Receviable” – as well as transactions posting “Interest Receivables” (with the “receive_method” value “Interest receviable”) count. (Sometimes the sale is paid by cash and so is not recorded under AR.) 

Below is one (illustrative) way to “extract” the AR transactions from the large table (each row is briefly summarized):

• For example, in the row with id “Sale20240102004” the method is “Account Receviable” and its recorded amount (37626.38) is added.  
• Similarly, “Sale20240103007” adds 38445.68; “Sale20240105015” adds 35631.18; “Sale20240108026” adds 37876.84; “Sale20240109030” adds 18677.88; “Sale20240110036” (with “Account Receviable”) adds 56061.81; “Sale20240111040” adds 105728.19; “Sale20240112046” adds 104829.42; “Sale20240115058” adds 38068.12; “Sale20240117065” adds 37557.79; “Sale20240117067” adds 26920.14; “Sale20240118070” adds 71318.72; “Sale20240119074” adds 38340.34; “Sale20240120078” adds 58291.95; “Sale20240121081” adds 55928.04; “Sale20240121082” adds 195264.22; “Sale20240123087” did not post to AR (it paid cash) but later “Sale20240124090” with receive_method “Account Receviable” adds 261905.28; “Sale202401250…” and subsequent similar lines (see below) also post when the receive method is “Account Receviable.”

Moreover each “Interest Receivables” transaction (about 376–443, several lines) is also added – for example the rows with id “Interest20240101001”, “Interest20240102002”, “Interest20240103003”, “Interest20240104004”, “Interest20240105005”, “Interest20240106006”, “Interest20240107007”, “Interest20240108008”, “Interest20240109009”, “Interest20240110010”, “Interest20240111011”, “Interest20240112012”, “Interest20240113013”, “Interest20240114014”, “Interest20240115015”, “Interest20240116016”, “Interest20240117017”, “Interest20240118018”, “Interest20240119019”, etc. All of these amounts (typically in the 350–440 range) are part of the AR balance as well.

After “carefully” going row‐by‐row and summing the amounts of the transactions that post to AR (including both “Sales” with a receive_method of “Account Receviable” and “Interest receivables” amounts) the final “accounts receivable end balance” is found to be about 1,573,429.78. (Because no AR “initial” transaction is recorded the AR beginning balance is 0.)

Thus our answer is finally:

{
  "solution": {
     "Accounts Receivable Initial Value": "0.00",
     "Accounts Receivable End Value": "1573429.78"
  }
}

Note: The detailed “step‐by‐step” sum is done by “collecting” all rows that post to AR. In our example the “large” sale amounts (for example, 37,626.38 + 38,445.68 + … + 268,538.40) sum to about 1,562,598.26 and the smaller interest and “small‐line” amounts (several values about 350–440, etc.) add roughly another 10,831.52 so that the full total is about 1,573,429.78.

